2026-03-06 | Minimum Window Substring

	Question
Given strings s and p, return the smallest substring of s containing all characters of p.

	Approach
1.	Use sliding window with two pointers:
		left and right.
2.	Create a frequency map for characters in p.
3.	Track how many characters from p are still required.
4.	Expand the window by moving right pointer:
		decrease frequency in map.
		if character was required → decrease required count.
5.	When required becomes 0:
		the current window contains all characters.
6.	Try shrinking from the left while still valid:
		update minimum length substring.
		increase frequency when removing characters.
		if a required character is removed → window invalid again.
7.	Continue until the end of the string.

	Time Complexity
	O(n)

	Space Complexity
	O(1) (alphabet size constant)

	Solution

class Solution {
public:
    string minWindow(string s, string p) {
        vector<int> freq(256, 0);

        for (char c : p)
            freq[c]++;

        int left = 0, right = 0;
        int required = p.size();
        int start = 0, minLen = INT_MAX;

        while (right < s.size()) {
            if (freq[s[right]] > 0)
                required--;

            freq[s[right]]--;
            right++;

            while (required == 0) {
                if (right - left < minLen) {
                    minLen = right - left;
                    start = left;
                }

                freq[s[left]]++;
                if (freq[s[left]] > 0)
                    required++;

                left++;
            }
        }

        if (minLen == INT_MAX)
            return "";

        return s.substr(start, minLen);
    }
};

	Key Insight
The sliding window dynamically expands to include required characters and shrinks to find the minimum valid window.  
This guarantees an optimal O(n) solution.
